More inquisitive people drew attention to the unprecedentedly wide scale of the arrests, the large number of police officers involved in them, as well as the atmosphere of secrecy in which the arrested persons were taken out. In the future, there was no news of the court or at least no charges; moreover, none of the detainees subsequently appeared in American prisons. Later, contradictory rumors spread about some supposedly extremely dangerous disease, concentration camps, and the placement of those arrested in numerous military and naval prisons, however, all these rumors had no real basis.